questiontext.text:
Suppose that we have a triangle of the following form.

Suppose that length \(AB = {@AB@}\)cm, length \(AC = {@AC@}\) and angle \(A = {@aa@}^\circ\), find the length of the side \(BC\). Give your answer to the nearest centimetre.

  • BC = [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] cm

generalfeedback.text: Here we use the cosine rule. Recall that \[ a^2 = b^2 + c^2 - 2bc \cos A \qquad \mbox{or} \qquad b^2 = a^2 + c^2 - 2ac \cos B \qquad \mbox{or} \qquad c^2 = a^2 + b^2 - 2ab \cos C. \] So in this case we have that length \(AB = c = {@AB@}\), length \(AC = b = {@AC@}\) and angle \(A = {@aa@}^\circ\). Thus inputting into the cosine rule we have \[ a^2 = BC^2 = {@AC^2@} + {@AB^2@} - 2 \cdot {@AC@} \cdot {@AB@} \cdot \cos {@aa@}^\circ. \] Hence \(BC = {@ta1@}\) to the nearest cm.
